# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: euclid-trucks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The **2007 General Motors Strike** was a labor union strike that lasted three days from September 23 to September 25, 2007, organized by the United Auto Workers (UAW) union.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW were engaged in talks with General Motors (GM) to negotiate a new labor contract but were unable to come to an agreement before the deadline.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Consequently, 73,000 workers walked out forcing 80 GM facilities in 30 states to cease operations.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] After the two day strike, the two parties reached an agreement in which the UAW union would assume the responsibility for managing retiree healthcare liabilities.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW previously went on strike against General Motors in 1970.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The automobile industry landscape in 2007 was drastically different to what it once was.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] GM's market share had been steadily decreasing as foreign automakers entered the market.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Foreign players secured over 50% of market share for the first time in history in July 2007.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] GM's foreign competitors Nissan, Honda, and Toyota increased their production within the United States.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Part of GM's struggles has been its relatively high costs of production.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] While many of the foreign manufacturers pay less in wages as most of their plants are not a part of a union, GM's labor contracts increase its costs per car by an estimated $2000 impacting its competitiveness.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] These costs can be attributed to worker pensions and healthcare programs the unions have negotiated.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The number of UAW members at GM has also steadily decreased as the company downsized.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time of the 2007 strike, the 73,000 workers at GM are far lower than the 400,000 workers GM employed when the UAW last went on strike in 1970.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW's lower overall membership was also caused by the increasing prevalence of non-unionized plants and factories belonging to foreign automakers.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] It once had over 1.5 million workers but by 2007, that number had shrunk to just several hundred thousand.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] General Motors' previous labor contract with the UAW union went up until September 14, 2007.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Both parties agreed to an extension of 10 days until September 24 as the UAW felt that negotiations were still progressing.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] However, following the end of this 10 day period, as negotiations came to a stalemate the UAW believed a strike was necessary as GM refused to acquiesce to the UAW's demands in regards to job security and worker benefits.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] General Motors' losing market share within the United States automobile market has forced the company to downsize the company.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] In the two years leading up to 2007, GM had incurred $12.3 billion in losses.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] In response, GM has since closed down numerous factories and laid off thousands of workers.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time of the strike, GM was also planning on cutting an additional 30,000 jobs in the coming year.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW wanted to ensure job security for the remaining GM workers and demanded for guarantees stipulating that those workers employed under the contract would stay employed until the contract expired.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Another issue of contention between GM and UAW was the company's liabilities to retirees in regards to their healthcare benefits.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] These liabilities amounted to $51 billion.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Both parties were in talks to discuss transferring these liabilities to a trust, which was GM's primary demand.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The establishment of a voluntary employee benefit association (VEBA) has been an idea that was widely embraced by GM's investors and managers.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Doing so what entail a large initial payment from GM but would allow it to remove workers healthcare benefits as a liability on its balance sheet.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] It was believed that removing these costs from the equation would allow GM to increase its competitiveness in the industry.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Immediately after the deadline had passed, the UAW union moved to a national strike that involved 73,000 workers walking out of an estimated 80 GM facilities.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] After the union announced the strike, negotiations continued that same afternoon lasting over five hours.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] In the UAW's press conference, its president Ron Gettelfinger expressed his disappointment in GM's management and their refusal to meet the union halfway.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] He believed that the UAW had no choice but to strike stating that: “There comes a point in time where you have to draw a line in the sand”.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Many saw this as the UAW refusing to roll over to management's demands from GM.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Gettelfinger also expressed that the UAW was willing to consider GM's request to form a trust to take on healthcare liabilities, and that job security remained the union's number one concern.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The effect of the strike was an operational halt that would otherwise produce 12,200 cars a day.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Concerns were raised regarding the effect of the strike on GM if an agreement wasn't reached.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The strike had the potential to influence GM supply chains and overseas plants that manufacture parts.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Nearby operations in Mexico and Canada would also suffer as a result.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The strike became a focus within the automobile industry as how it played it out would likely affect negotiations the UAW would later have with Ford and Chrysler given the vulnerable state of the United States’ auto companies.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Despite the strike, Michael Robinet, the vice president of CSM Worldwide and an expert on global vehicle forecasts, predicted that GM would not have any issues with a shortage of vehicle production.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] In fact, he expected that the company would not experience issues related to inventory shortages for two to three weeks should the strike continue as a result of no agreement being reached.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time, GM's inventory levels were generally higher than that of their competitors, a point that many linked to the company's poor sales in recent months leading up to the strike.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] On the first day of the strike, GM's stock closed 20 cents lower in the trading session, wiping out what was originally a gain of 2.6% earlier on in the day.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The consensus amongst analysts evaluating GM's position in the strike was that while a long strike would be highly detrimental for the company as it seeks to turn its business around and become more profitable.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] With that said, many believed that GM would still be well positioned to endure a strike that was shorter in nature.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] On September 26, it was announced that early that morning, the UAW and GM reached a deal.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Specifics of the deal were not made available, however the headline for GM was that the UAW had agreed to the establishment of a VEBA that would assume the retiree healthcare liabilities worth $51 billion.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Gettelfinger described that job guarantees were made by GM although the details were not disclosed.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] After reaching the deal, the UAW's executives stated their intention to meet again on the 28th of September to discuss and approve the contract.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] If successful, the contract would then be moved to be voted on by the workers in the union to finalize the agreement.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Gettelfinger expressed his confidence that GM's workers would vote in favor of this newly negotiated contract.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Had the contract not been approved by both the UAW leaders and the workers, the UAW made it clear that the strike would continue.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] It was reported that members who had information regarding the details of the VEBA disclosed that the trust would be funded by a combination of various assets including cash and GM stock.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The trust's establishment would be subject to approval by the Security and Exchange Commission and the relevant court of law.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The approval process was expected to last over a year with the earliest completion date being sometime in 2009.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The agreement involved allowing GM to access the pension fund for the purpose of reimbursing retirees for the increased healthcare benefits offered in the years preceding the deal, as the pension was seen as being overfunded.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Newspapers also reported sources that indicated some of the terms of the new contract involved a steep decrease in the wages of lower tier workers along with lower signing bonuses.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Other sources confirmed that the two parties agreed to meet on a yearly basis to evaluate and discuss the healthcare trust.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] It was reported that GM was willing to make additional contributions to the fund if it was determined to be necessary if the amount was within a range the company considered reasonable.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] It was also expected that the leaders of the UAW would discuss the details of the GM contract with labor officials at the other large automobile manufacturers, Ford and Chrysler, as a part of a series of labor contract negotiations within the industry.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time, the UAW union was also in negotiations with them over new labor contracts although little progress had been made.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Many experts pointed out the possibility that both Ford and Chrysler could establish similar VEBA trusts which would reduce liabilities, something that many of these companies have looked forward to.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] GM believed that the agreement would allow them to "significantly improve its manufacturing competitiveness".
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Investor sentiment regarding the deal being reached was generally positive for GM as they have been proponents for the establishment of the VEBA trust.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] After the deal was reached between GM and the UAW union, the stock price of GM increased by 4.2% in the morning of that trading session, and closed with a 9% rise reaching its highest mark in ten weeks.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] GM's bond prices also increased following the news.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] The stock price of Ford increased by more than 6% in the same session, likely linked to investor expectations that a similar deal would be reached in their negotiations with the UAW.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Credit rating agencies shared a similarly positive response to the deal.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Fitch was in discussions to lower GM's rating and that of some of its suppliers, however decided to hold off after the new deal was announced.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Standard and Poor’s discussed the possibility of increasing GM's long term rating moving forward.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] GM pointed out their healthcare spending in the previous year totaled $4.8 billion, an amount that could have been spent towards launching six vehicle models or building an additional four manufacturing plants.
[src:euclid-trucks/2007-general-motors-strike] Wall street analysts were expecting GM to benefit from increased healthcare cost savings amounting to $3 billion annually as a consequence of the newly established VEBA trust.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The **2019 General Motors strike** began September 15, 2019, with the walkout of 48,000 United Automobile Workers from some 50 plants in the United States.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] Demands by workers included increased job security, gateway for temporary workers to become permanent, better pay and retaining healthcare benefits.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike lasted six weeks, and ended when GM conceded to union demands on wage growth and health care costs because the new contract allows GM to close three factories: the Lordstown Assembly plant, the Baltimore Transmission plant, and the Warren Transmission plant.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] This strike constituted the first major labor action in the American automotive industry in a decade.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The last strike coordinated by the UAW targeting General Motors occurred in 2007.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] During the Great Recession and economic uncertainty that followed, unionized automotive workers accepted concessions to allow GM and other companies to recover.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] Though GM has since received large tax breaks and returned to profitability, worker compensation remained stagnant, and the UAW took umbrage with the company's decisions to shutter American facilities and move some jobs abroad.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The contract between the UAW and General Motors expired September 14, and the strike began at 11:59 p.m. on September 15, 2019.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] A two-day difference between contract expiration and the beginning of a strike is unusually short, but likely motivated by the prolonged negotiations between management and the union.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike involved 48,000 GM employees.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] On September 17, GM stopped providing health insurance to 55,000 union members, forcing the UAW to pay for COBRA.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] On September 26, it was announced that GM would start to pay health insurance again to people on strike.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] On October 16, it was announced that GM and the UAW agreed on a new labor contract that ended the month-long strike.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] However, the agreement between GM and UAW had not been officially approved, and workers who were still on strike said that they would wait until the deal had been ratified before they returned to their jobs.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The new contract was ratified by UAW members on October 25, ending the strike.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike lasted six weeks, and ended when GM conceded to union demands on wage growth and healthcare costs because the new contract allowed GM to close three factories: the Lordstown plant, the Baltimore plant, and a transmission plant in Warren.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] An analyst for Credit Suisse estimated that GM could lose as much as $50 million each day the strike continued, while other analysts estimated daily losses could be as high as $100 million per day.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] GM's share of the automobile market had decreased from 30% in the late 1990s to 17% by 2019, meaning the strike likely had fewer implications for the economy at large when compared to labor actions in the past.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike was also predicted to possibly lead to impacts on GM factories abroad, which rely on parts produced in American factories closed because of the strike, and on suppliers such as Canada-based Magna International.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] At the beginning of the strike, GM had roughly 83 days' worth of inventory available for sale, temporarily insulating its supply chain from the impact of the strike.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] The Teamsters refused to deliver GM cars during the strike, in solidarity with GM workers.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] Members of the Trump administration, including Larry Kudlow and Peter Navarro, allegedly intervened in negotiations; however, GM and the White House have both denied Kudlow and Navarro's involvement.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] On September 21, Senator Elizabeth Warren, running at the time for the Democratic nomination for President of the United States, joined a UAW picket line in Detroit.
[src:euclid-trucks/2019-general-motors-strike] Other Democratic contenders for the nomination including Senator Bernie Sanders, former vice-president Joe Biden, Senator Amy Klobuchar, and Representative Tim Ryan, also visited picket lines during the strike.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The portion of the building at the corner of 57th Street and Broadway was built for car manufacturer Aaron T.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The section belonging to the former Peerless Motor Company is an L-shaped structure wrapping around the A.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street is 11 stories tall; the former Demarest section rises nine stories, while the Peerless section contains a partial tenth floor and an additional two-story tower.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street contains a steel-frame curtain wall, concrete piers, and a facade of glazed architectural terracotta.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Inside, both of the former structures had automotive storerooms at ground level and warehouses and repair facilities on the upper floors.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Demarest and Peerless buildings were constructed simultaneously in 1909.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] General Motors (GM) bought both buildings in 1918 and combined them internally.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] After GM constructed other buildings in Manhattan, 224 West 57th Street was renamed the Argonaut Building to avoid confusion.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Hearst Corporation bought 224 West 57th Street in 1977 and housed its Hearst Magazine department there until 2006.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated the building as a city landmark in 2000.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The building was renovated from 2008 to 2011 and subsequently became the headquarters of Open Society Foundations.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street is on the southeastern corner of Broadway and 57th Street, two blocks south of Columbus Circle and Central Park in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The building carries the addresses 1758–1770 Broadway and 224–228 West 57th Street.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The lot occupies an area of 14,200 feet (4,300 m), with frontage of 136 feet (41 m) on Broadway and 141 feet (43 m) on 57th Street.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The lot measures 116 feet (35 m) along its eastern lot line and 91.6 feet (27.9 m) on its southern lot line.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street abuts the American Society of Civil Engineers' Society House to the east and faces Central Park Tower to the north.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Other nearby buildings include the American Fine Arts Society (also known as the Art Students League of New York building) and Osborne Apartments to the northeast; Rodin Studios and 888 Seventh Avenue to the east; and 1740 Broadway to the south.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] In the 20th century, the area was part of Manhattan's "Automobile Row", a stretch of Broadway extending mainly between Times Square at 42nd Street and Sherman Square at 72nd Street.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Before the first decade of the 20th century, the area was occupied mostly by equestrian industries and was described by *The New York Times* as "thoroughly lifeless".
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] By 1907, the *Times* characterized this section of Broadway as having "almost a solid line of motor vehicle signs all the way from Times Square to Sherman Square".
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] In the late 1900s and early 1910s, several large automobile showrooms, stores, and garages were built on Broadway, including the B.F.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Goodrich showroom (later part of Central Park Tower) and the U.S.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Rubber Company Building just north of 224 West 57th Street.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Both of the formerly separate buildings comprising 224 West 57th Street, the Demarest and Peerless Buildings, were designed by Francis H.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Demarest Company section takes up the corner lot, measuring 66 by 116 feet (20 by 35 m), while the Peerless Company section occupies an L-shaped lot around the Demarest Building and measures 70 feet (21 m) wide on Broadway by 25 feet (7.6 m) wide on 57th Street.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The structure was erected by the George A.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Fuller Company with Purdy and Henderson as the consulting engineer.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The design of 224 West 57th Street's constituent structures incorporates many Gothic Revival and Romanesque Revival architectural details, to complement each other and the now-demolished Broadway Tabernacle church building to the south.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Most of 224 West 57th Street is nine stories tall, although there is a tenth story atop part of the building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street's eastern section, belonging to the former Peerless Building, contains a penthouse rising two additional stories above the main roof.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] In total, 224 West 57th Street is 12 stories tall and has a roof height of 132.91 feet (40.51 m).
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The facade, made almost entirely of terracotta, contains many decorative elements created by the New York Architectural Terra-Cotta Company.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The northern and western elevations or sides of 224 West 57th Street are both subdivided into five groupings, each with three bays, and are connected by a canted corner.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The northern two groupings on Broadway and the western four groupings on 57th Street belonged to the Demarest Building, while the southern three groupings on Broadway and the easternmost grouping on 57th Street was part of the Peerless Building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The southern facade, was originally visible behind the nave of the Broadway Tabernacle.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] At the first and second stories, each of the five triple-width groupings are subdivided by double-height pilasters with cartouches at their tops.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] As built, these wide groupings originally contained automotive storefronts or entrances for pedestrians or vehicles.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The easternmost grouping on 57th Street has a glass-and-metal doorway under a transom, and is flanked by inscribed bronze plaques with the building's name and address.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The corner entrance at Broadway and 57th Street has glass-and-metal door under a transom.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The facade has various ornamentation on the third through ninth stories, including colonettes, arched windows, cornices, and brackets.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The second-southernmost grouping of the Broadway elevation has an oriel window spanning the fifth through seventh floors.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Above the ninth floor, there are pediments over the six groupings comprising the former Demarest Building, and parapets over the four groupings that make up the former Peerless Building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The southern elevation is clad in terracotta, but because of the presence of a neighboring building, only the westernmost two bays of the southern elevation are visible.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The eastern elevation is made largely of tan brick.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The two-story penthouse above the Peerless Building's easternmost section is clad in tan brick and contains terracotta trim, quoined pilasters, round arches with keyed surrounds, and tile signs on the western elevation.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] There were formerly also tile signs on the eastern and northern elevations of the penthouse.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street has 164,000 square feet (15,200 m2) of usable interior space.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] This includes 6,000 square feet (560 m2) at ground level, 4,800 square feet (450 m2) in the tenth-floor penthouse, and between 10,000 and 18,000 square feet (930 and 1,670 m2) on each of the other floors.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Both constituent structures are supported by an internal steel frame atop concrete foundation piers, with the facade acting as a curtain wall.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Upon completion, the corner Demarest Building had offices as well as carriage and automobile warehouses.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] There was one elevator each for pedestrians and vehicles.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The surrounding Peerless Building had a double-height ground-floor salesroom, with a gilded ceiling and marble walls and columns.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The second through tenth floors respectively contained vehicle stock, new cars, used cars, an inspection studio, an upholstery department, repair shops, more repair shops, a painting department, and a blacksmith shop.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless Building had two vehicle elevators, one passenger elevator, and a turntable.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Realty, a company associated with builder George A.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Fuller, purchased five lots at the southeast corner of 57th Street and Broadway in 1902.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The lots had come under the ownership of Robert E.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Dowling by 1905, when Dowling transferred these lots to the Island Realty Company.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Island Realty planned to build an apartment hotel on the site, although this ultimately did not happen.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The easternmost section of the lot was sold to the American Society of Civil Engineers in 1905 to make room for an extension of their Society House.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless and Demarest companies were among the companies that moved to Automobile Row in the first decade of the 20th century.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless Motor Car Company of New York, a subsidiary of the Peerless Motor Company of Cleveland, Ohio, was headquartered at 220 West 41st Street by 1905.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Demarest, was headquartered on Fifth Avenue and 33rd Street prior to the construction of its 57th Street showroom.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] By December 1908, the Demarest Company leased the three corner lots at Broadway and 57th Street, intending to build a showroom and shop there.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] That month, Kimball was hired to prepare plans for a pair of buildings to be occupied by the Peerless and Demarest companies.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Doan Realty, a subsidiary of the Peerless Company, bought the two lots surrounding the Demarest Company's land by mid-1909.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Realty also sold off the corner plots under the new Demarest Building to the Matoaka Realty Company.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Construction on the buildings commenced in March 1909.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Demarest Company's building was completed by that June, while the Peerless Company's building was completed three months later in September.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless Building represented an investment of $1 million, and collectively employed 250 workers upon completion.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Peerless wrote that the new building allowed them to modify, repair, upholster, paint, and store cars "under one roof", and the word "Peerless" was mounted on the northern face of the Peerless Building's tower.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] One of the Peerless Building's two vehicle elevators was removed in 1912.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Both the Demarest and Peerless companies stayed in their respective showrooms for less than a decade after their completion.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Peerless had moved out by 1915, and Demarest stopped leasing its showroom by 1917.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The Chevrolet Company, the automotive division of General Motors (GM), leased the Demarest Building starting in May 1917, and hired Henry Janeway Hardenbergh to renovate the Demarest Building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The following October, Chevrolet bought the Peerless and Demarest buildings at a combined $1.5 million.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Sources vary on the sequence of the subsequent renovation.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) and the *Real Estate Record and Guide* wrote that GM hired Hardenbergh for the renovations, with plans for the existing elevators and stairs to be taken out and replaced with three passenger elevators.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] However, *The New York Times* stated that the buildings were renovated by J.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Phelan, and that while the Peerless Building's original vehicular entrance on 57th Street was removed, the Demarest Building's vehicular elevator was left intact.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] According to the *Times*, the upper floors were renovated and the blacksmiths' shop became a dining room for executives.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The two structures became known as the General Motors Building at 224 West 57th Street, and a tile sign with the words "General Motors Corporation" was added to the Peerless Building's tower.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street thus served as General Motors' headquarters in New York City, and contained GM's general offices as well as those of Chevrolet, the General Motors Acceptance Corporation, and the General Motors Export Company.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] By 1926, GM was developing 3 Columbus Circle, a 26-story skyscraper diagonally across from 224 West 57th Street, for use as its New York City headquarters.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] GM's offices were relocated to 3 Columbus Circle in 1927, and 224 West 57th Street became known as the Argonaut Building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] GM continued to use the Argonaut Building as a showroom, opening a Cadillac and LaSalle showroom on the ground level in 1935.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] At that point, vehicle elevators between the basement and the third floor were installed.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] According to the building's subsequent owners, the first built-in car radios were sold inside the showroom in 1938.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] During the 1940s, the Automobile Merchants Association took space in the building, as did the United States Office of War Information and the *Voice of America*.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The *Voice* and the Office of War Information had leased all of the office floors during World War II, but GM retook most of the space after the end of the war.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The second and third floors of the Argonaut Building became office space in 1964, and the ground-level showroom operated through the late 1970s.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Although General Motors completed a new headquarters and showroom building at 767 Fifth Avenue in 1968, GM stated that it would retain the Argonaut Building after the completion of the new structure.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] By the 1970s, GM had moved its divisions in the Argonaut Building to other locations.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Hearst Communications started to lease space in the Argonaut Building in 1975, and purchased the property outright two years later in July 1977.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The LPC designated 224 West 57th Street, along with the U.S.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Rubber Company Building and the Studebaker Building in Brooklyn, as official city landmarks on December 19, 2000.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The terracotta facade was repaired and painted with a white coating in 2006.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Although Christopher Gray of *The New York Times* said conservators usually disapproved of applying coating to terracotta, the facade had already been coated previously, so the modification was approved by the LPC.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Also in 2006, Hearst moved its headquarters one block west to the Hearst Tower, following the completion of that building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street was leased by foreign developer M1 Real Estate in 2008 for 99 years.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] At the time, Gensler was already planning to renovate the building for $45 million; the building was thus vacated, with ground-floor tenant Duane Reade moving out.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] A branch of TD Bank signed a lease for the ground floor space in 2009, and M1 purchased 224 West 57th Street from Hearst for $85 million the next year.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Gensler's renovation was completed in 2011 and received a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Gold award from the U.S.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] This made 224 West 57th Street one of a few buildings over 100 years old to receive LEED Gold certification.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] George Soros's Open Society Foundations leased all the office space at the Argonaut Building in September 2011, with the former ground-floor showroom housing a bank by that time.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Tirmizi Campbell subsequently renovated the interior space for OSF's use, with the project being completed in 2013.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Eretz Group purchased 224 West 57th Street from M1 Real Estate in 2015 for $214 million, and the owners secured a $145 million loan for the building in 2018.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] By mid-2022, Open Society Foundations was still the only office tenant in the Argonaut Building.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Soros Fund Management moved to foreclose on the building's mortgage in April 2024.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] That June, the delinquent mortgages on the building were sold by Deutsche Bank and another German lender to the George Soros Family office.
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] Shortly after the Peerless and Demarest buildings opened, *Architects' and Builders' Magazine* wrote that the designs complemented the Broadway Tabernacle "in a harmonious and satisfactory manner".
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] The magazine wrote that the Gothic designs differed from each other "in every detail", but "in spirit conveys the same idea".
[src:euclid-trucks/224-west-57th-street] In 2007, Gray wrote in *The New York Times* that the facade, which complemented the long-demolished Broadway Tabernacle, "seems a bit out of place amid the traffic at one of the busiest intersections in Midtown".
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] United Motors Corporation was formed by William C.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Durant in 1916 as an automotive component and accessory holding company.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Durant was the owner of Buick and founder of General Motors in 1908.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] After he lost control of General Motors in 1910, he founded Chevrolet in 1911 with Louis Chevrolet and the profits from this permitted him to regain control of GM in 1916.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] At approximately the same time, he assembled United Motors.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Durant's founding of United Motors has parallels in his earlier experience in the horse-drawn carriage industry in Michigan.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] In the late 19th century he was co-owner of the Durant-Dort Carriage Company, one of the nation's leading carriage manufacturers.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Concerned that they could not source components and raw materials at affordable prices or in sufficient quantities, Durant-Dort created a vertically-integrated operation owning hardwood forests and manufacturing its own bodies, wheels, axles, upholstery, springs, varnish and whips.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] United Motors initially included Alfred P.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Sloan's Hyatt Roller Bearing Company (antifriction roller bearings), New Departure Manufacturing Company (ball bearings), Remy Electric Company (electrical starting, lighting, and ignition equipment), Charles Kettering and Edward A.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Deeds' Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company (DELCO automotive ignition, starters and generators), and the Perlman Rim Corporation.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Sloan, who had been president of Hyatt, as president of United Motors.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] In the next two years, Sloan bought the Harrison Radiator Corporation, Lovell-McConnell Manufacturing Company (renamed Klaxon company to make Klaxon horns) in September 1916, and organized United Motors Service to sell and service the entire line of products nationwide.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] United Motors was originally independent of General Motors, selling to all manufacturers until 1918, when the company was acquired by General Motors for $45 million (three quarters debentures and one quarter common shares) and integrated into GM on December 31, 1918.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] United Motors became United Motors Service and continued to operate essentially as it had before.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] However, all of its production was now devoted to GM's brands.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Sloan continued as the division manager, which carried with it a GM vice-president title and a position on the GM board.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] In 1923 he became President of General Motors and was Chairman when he retired in 1956.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Charles Kettering, co-founder of Delco, was head of research at General Motors for 27 years.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Harrison was President of Harrison Radiator until his death in 1927.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Durant lost control of GM for the final time in 1920.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] United Motors Service would become a fully integrated division of General Motors in 1944.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Around 1960, the division's name was changed to United Delco.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] With the Delco name becoming more well known with consumers, the “Delco” name was incorporated into all of the division's branches (Delco Remy, Delco Harrison, Delco Packard (Packard Electric), Delco Moraine).
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] A red and blue semicircular logo was implemented, designed by Lance Wyman (who would later famously design the graphic identity for the 1968 Mexico City Olympics, among other projects).
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] In 1899, Albert Champion came to the U.S. as a champion bicycle racer.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] He founded the Champion Spark Plug Company with the Stranahan brothers in 1905 and began production in 1907.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Durant of the Buick Motor Co. asked to see some of Champion's prototypes.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Buick at that time was using Rajah spark plugs.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Durant thought they could manufacture spark plugs to Champion's design cheaper than buying them from Rajah, and set Champion up in a workshop in Flint, Michigan as part of the budding auto industry there.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Champion went to work producing spark plugs to be used in Buick automobiles.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] Champion and Durant formed "Champion Ignition Co." Very shortly later, the Stranahan brothers ("Champion Spark Plug Co.") informed them they could not use the name "Champion" as they had it trademarked, so Champion changed the name to Champion's initials, AC Spark Plug.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] In 1927 AC Spark Plugs was bought by General Motors.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] In 1974, in an effort to streamline its operations and marketing, General Motors merged AC Spark Plug's aftersales operation with United Delco to create the new AC-Delco (Albert Champion Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company.) AC-Delco then marketed various AC and Delco-branded products.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] The hyphen was dropped and ACDelco received a new logo and marketing initiative.
[src:euclid-trucks/acdelco] The "AC" bullseye and semicircular Delco logo disappeared from product packaging.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:euclid-trucks/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:euclid-trucks/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan wrote his memoir, *My Years with General Motors*, in the 1950s.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Like Henry Ford, Sloan is remembered with a complex mixture of admiration for his accomplishments, appreciation for his philanthropy, and unease or reproach regarding his attitudes during the interwar period and World War II.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Born in New Haven, Connecticut, Sloan studied electrical engineering initially at Brooklyn Polytechnic Institute, then transferred to and graduated from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in 1895.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In 1898, Sloan married Irene Jackson of Roxbury, Massachusetts.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The couple not having children is speculation.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan became president and owner of Hyatt Roller Bearing, a company that made roller- and ball-bearings, in 1899 when his father and another investor bought out the company from the previous owner.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] An account stated that Sloan persuaded his father to buy a controlling interest in the company for $5,000 and let him manage it.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Oldsmobile was Hyatt's first automotive customer, with many other companies soon following suit.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] By 1903, he was said to have summoned the young Sloan and castigated him for delivering inconsistent quality of his bearings' tolerances.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] According to Sloan, this conversation allowed him to gain "a genuine conception of what mass production should really mean." The Ford Model T also used Hyatt bearings and for a time, over half of the company's bearings went to Ford.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In 1916, Hyatt merged with other companies into United Motors Company, which soon became part of General Motors.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan became vice-president of GM, then president (1923), and finally chairman of the board (1937).
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In 1934, he established the philanthropic, nonprofit Alfred P.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] GM under Sloan became famous for managing diverse operations with financial statistics such as return on investment; these measures were introduced to GM by Donaldson Brown, a protege of GM vice-president John J.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Raskob came to GM as an advisor to Pierre S. du Pont and the du Pont corporation; the latter was a principal investor in GM whose executives largely ran GM in the 1920s.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan is credited with establishing annual styling changes, from which came the concept of planned obsolescence.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In 1919, he and his corporate deputies created the General Motors Acceptance Corporation, a financing arm that practically invented the auto loan credit system, that allowed car buyers to bypass having to save for years to buy Ford's affordable car.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] These concepts, along with Ford's resistance to the change in the 1920s, propelled GM to industry-sales leadership by the early 1930s, a position it retained for over 70 years.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Under Sloan's direction, GM became the largest industrial enterprise the world had ever known.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In the 1930s GM, long hostile to unionization, confronted its workforce—newly organized and ready for labor rights—in an extended contest for control.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan was averse to violence of the sort associated with Henry Ford.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] He preferred spying, investing in an internal undercover apparatus to gather information and monitor labor union activity.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] When workers organized the massive Flint sit-down strike in 1936, Sloan found that espionage had little value in the face of such open tactics, and instead the successful strike legitimized the United Auto Workers as the exclusive bargaining representative for GM workers.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan Museum, showcasing the evolution of the automobile industry and traveling galleries, is in Flint, Michigan.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan maintained an office in 30 Rockefeller Plaza in Rockefeller Center, now known as the Comcast Building.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] He retired as GM chairman on April 2, 1956.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] His memoir and management treatise, *My Years with General Motors*, was more or less finished around this time; but GM's legal staff, who feared that it would be used to support an antitrust case against GM, held up its publication for nearly a decade.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan was inducted into the Junior Achievement U.S.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan Foundation, a philanthropic nonprofit organization.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan gave extensively to programs in business management.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The world's first university-based executive education program, the Sloan Fellows, started in 1931 at MIT under the sponsorship of a Sloan Foundation grant.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] MIT opened a School of Industrial Management in 1952 with the charge of educating the "ideal manager", and the school was renamed the Alfred P.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Additional grants established a Sloan Institute of Hospital Administration in 1955 at Cornell University, a Sloan Fellows Program at Stanford Graduate School of Business in 1957, and at London Business School in 1965.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] They became degree programs in 1976, awarding the degree of Master of Science in Management.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan's name also lives on in the Sloan-Kettering Institute and Cancer Center in New York.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In 1951, Sloan received the Hundred Year Association of New York's Gold Medal Award "in recognition of outstanding contributions to the City of New York".
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The Sloan Foundation bankrolled the 1956 Warner Bros. cartoon *Yankee Dood It*, which promotes mass production.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In the late 1940s, the foundation made a grant to Harding College (now Harding University) in Searcy, Arkansas.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The foundation wanted to fund the production of a series of short films extolling the virtues of capitalism and the American way of life.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] This resulted in the production of a series of animated cartoons by John Sutherland that were released on the 16mm non-theatrical market, and also distributed theatrically in 35mm by Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The Sloan Foundation's programs and interests are in the areas of science and technology, standard of living, economic performance, and education and careers in science and technology.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] For the year ending December 31, 2023, the total assets of the Sloan Foundation had a market value of about $2.38 billion.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] As of 2017, the Sloan Foundation has made three grants, of $3 million each, to the Wikimedia Foundation (WMF).
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] These are some of the largest grants WMF has received.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] According to Edwin Black, Sloan was one of the central, behind-the-scenes 1934 founders of the American Liberty League, a political organization whose stated goal was to defend the Constitution, and which opposed Franklin D.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In turn, the league financed other groups with openly more extreme agendas.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] One such group was the Sentinels of the Republic, to which Sloan himself donated $1,000.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] After a Congressional investigation into this group went public in 1936, Sloan issued a statement pledging not to further support the Sentinels.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Also according to Black, Sloan continued to personally fund and organize fund-raising for the National Association of Manufacturers, which was critical of the New Deal.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] According to O'Toole (1995), Sloan built a very objective organization, one that paid significant attention to "policies, systems, and structures and not enough to people, principles, and values.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan, the quintessential engineer, had worked out all the intricacies and contingencies of a foolproof system." But this system left out employees and society.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] One consequence of this management philosophy was a culture that resisted change.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Proof that the system did not remain foolproof forever was seen in GM's problems of the 1980s, 1990s, and 2000s.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In fact, Sloan's memoir and management treatise, *My Years With General Motors*, foresaw some of these problems.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan implied that only vigilant, intelligent management could meet them successfully.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] He predicted that *remaining* at the top of its industry and the economy would prove a bigger challenge for GM than getting there, and he was right.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] But he also seemed confident that GM's management style under his leadership, if continued and adapted, could meet these challenges.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] He said, "There have been and always will be many opportunities to fail in the automobile industry.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The circumstances of the ever-changing market and ever-changing product are capable of breaking any business organization if that organization is unprepared for change—indeed, in my opinion, if it has not provided procedures for anticipating change.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In General Motors these procedures are provided by the central management, which is in a position to appraise the broad long-term trends of the market. ...
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] As these words of Sloan (1964) show in juxtaposition with the words of Peter F.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Drucker (1946), Sloan (and his fellow GM executives) never agreed with the lessons Drucker drew from his study of GM management during the war.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] But unlike many GM executives, Sloan did not put Drucker on his blacklist for writing the 1946 book; Drucker, in his new introduction to the 1990 republishing of Sloan's memoir, said, "When his associates attacked me in a meeting called to discuss the book, Sloan immediately rose to my defense.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] 'I fully agree with you,' he said to his colleagues.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] But he did precisely what he told us he would do when we asked him in.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Drucker said, "He asked for my opinions and carefully listened—and he never once took my advice." History seems to have vindicated Drucker in his belief that Sloan's faith in rationality alone—and in the ability of other white-collar managers to be as astute as he was—was over-ardent.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] 40 years later, the management and board of directors that ran the original General Motors Corporation into the ground by 2009 were *not* "in a position to appraise the broad long-term trends of the market"—or were in that position, but not doing the job successfully therein.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] O'Toole described Sloan's style as follows: "[W]hereas Taylor occasionally backs off to justify his ardor for efficiency in human terms, not once does Sloan make reference to any other values.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Freedom, equality, humanism, stability, community, tradition, religion, patriotism, family, love, virtue, nature—all are ignored.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In the one personal element in the book, he makes passing reference to his wife: he abandons her on the first day of a European vacation to return to business in Detroit.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In 2005, Sloan's work at GM came under criticism for creating a complicated accounting system that prevents the implementation of lean manufacturing methods.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Essentially, the criticism is that by using Sloan's methods a company will value inventory just the same as cash, and thus there is no penalty for building up inventory.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Carrying excessive inventory is detrimental to a company's operation and induces significant hidden costs.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] This criticism must be viewed in the context that it is provided in hindsight.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] During the period in which Sloan advocated carrying what would now be considered excess inventory, the industrial and transportation infrastructure would not support what is now known as just-in-time inventory.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] During this period, the auto industry experienced incredible growth as the public eagerly sought to purchase this life-changing utility known as the automobile.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] The cost of lost sales due to lack of inventory was likely greater than the cost of carrying excess inventory.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan's system seems to have been widely adopted because of its advance over previous methods.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In his memoir, Sloan (who acknowledged that he was not a trained accountant) said the system that he implemented in the early 1920s was far better than what it replaced.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Systems similar to GM's were implemented by other major companies, especially in the United States, and they eventually undermined the ability to compete with companies that used different accounting, according to Waddell & Bodek's 2005 analysis.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan's memoir, particularly Chapter 8, "The development of financial controls", indicates that Sloan and GM appreciated the financial dangers of excess inventory even as early as the 1920s.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] But Waddell & Bodek's 2005 analysis indicates that this theory was not successfully implemented in GM's practice.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] For all the intellectual understanding, the reality remained slow inventory turnover and an accounting system that functionally treated inventory similarly to cash.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In August 1938, a senior executive for General Motors, James D.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Mooney, received the Grand Cross of the German Eagle for his distinguished service to the Reich.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] "Nazi armaments chief Albert Speer told a congressional investigator that Germany could not have attempted its September 1939 blitzkrieg of Poland without the performance-boosting additive technology provided by Alfred P.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] During the war, GM's Opel Brandenburg facilities produced Ju 88 bombers, trucks, land mines and torpedo detonators for Nazi Germany.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Charles Levinson, formerly deputy director of the European office of the CIO, alleged that Sloan remained on the board of Opel.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan's memoir presents a different picture of Opel's wartime role.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] According to Sloan, Opel was nationalized, along with most other industrial activity owned or co-owned by foreign interests, by the German state soon after the outbreak of war.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] But Opel was never factually nationalized and the GM-appointed directors and management remained unchanged throughout the Nazi period including the war, dealing with other GM companies in Axis and Allied countries including the United States.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan presents Opel at the end of the war as a black box to GM's American management, an organization with which the Americans had had no contact for five years.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] According to Sloan, GM in Detroit debated whether to even try to run Opel in the postwar era, or to leave to the interim West German government the question of who would pick up the pieces.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Defending the German investment strategy as "highly profitable", Sloan told shareholders in 1939 that GM's continued industrial production for the Nazi government was merely sound business practice.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In a letter to a concerned shareholder, Sloan said that the manner in which the Nazi government ran Germany "should not be considered the business of the management of General Motors. ...
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] We must conduct ourselves as a German organization. ...
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] As the war drew to an end, most economists and New Deal policy makers assumed that without continued massive government spending, the prewar Great Depression and its huge unemployment would return.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] Sloan felt otherwise and predicted a postwar boom.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] He pointed to workers' savings and pent-up demand, and predicted a huge jump in national income and a rise in standard of living.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] In line with his predictions, and despite a precipitous cutback in government spending and the wholesale closure of defense plants, the economy boomed.
[src:euclid-trucks/alfred-p-sloan] One of the greatest periods of economic expansion in US history resulted.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The **Euclid Trucks** was a manufacturer which specialized in heavy equipment for earthmoving, particularly dump trucks, loaders and wheel tractor-scrapers.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Known for its distinctive bright green paint scheme, it operated in the United States from the 1920s to the 1950s, when it was purchased by General Motors.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The firm was later bought by Hitachi Construction Machinery.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The Euclid Company of Euclid, Ohio, made specifically designed off-road heavy haulers, compared with other companies that modified on-road trucks for off-road earth-hauling.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The Euclid Crane and Hoist Co., formed in 1909 and owned by George A.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Armington and his five sons, had become a large, respected and profitable operation by the early 1920s.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] It introduced the Euclid Automatic Rotary Scraper in 1924, soon followed by the Euclid Wheeler (wheeled) scraper.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Those earthmoving products were conceived by George's eldest son, Arthur, who steered the company into the earthmoving field.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The two models of scrapers were well received, and a third model, the Euclid Contractors Special, designed to cope with hard ground, was even more successful.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] In 1926, the Armingtons formed Euclid Inc., the Road Machinery Division of Euclid Crane and Hoist, to cater especially to the off-road hauler market.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Arthur and his father, George, had built a successful prototype crawler, and tested it on the family farm, but the crawler design was dropped, for reasons unknown.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Large public works construction programs in 1927 and 1928 required large excavations, thus enhancing the success of the Euclid Road Machinery division.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid produced crawler wagons on tracks (similar to Athey Wagons) known as Euclid Tu-Way haulers.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The crawler track speed restriction was a problem, and the next version used steel wheels for improved speed.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] George Armington Jr was a keen hydraulics designer, and produced the first hydraulic Euclid dumpers circa 1930.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The Great Depression did not affect Euclid greatly, and the expansion of the earthmoving portion of the Euclid business led to the incorporation of the Euclid Road Machinery Co., on July 11, 1931.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] That company remained a subsidiary of Euclid Armington Corp, until January 1, 1933, when the companies were separated.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid Road Machinery became a producer of fast, off-road earthmoving haulers.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid produced its first specially designed, 7-yard (6.4 m)-long, off-road dump truck, the Model 1Z, in January 1934.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] It was powered by a 100 horsepower (75 kW) Waukesha gasoline engine, and used an extremely heavy-duty, Euclid rear axle, fitted with a new 17.5 x 24 tire, which had just been released by the tire industry.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Mack had produced a 14-yard (13 m)-long, heavy duty off-road hauler in 1931, specifically for the Boulder Dam project (the Model AP Super-Duty), but it was basically a beefed-up, road-going, chain-drive AC Bulldog Mack.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The next Euclid design was an articulated, tractor/trailer, in the style of the Caterpillar DW10 bottom dumper.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid made thousands of off-road haulers and scrapers.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Improved and larger designs helped it become a significant international corporation by the early 1950s.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] In 1950, a separate UK-based company, Euclid Great Britain, was established.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] A factory specialising in off-road haulers was opened in Motherwell, Scotland.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] In 1953, the Euclid Corporation was purchased by General Motors, in what the leaders of both companies saw as an advantageous deal, given their complementary product lines.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The deal came about due to GM's desire to enter the earthmoving manufacturing field, and the realisation by the Armington family that a GM takeover would provide capital and enhanced design capability.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The GM takeover was announced on September 30, 1953, with an official takeover date of January 1, 1954.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Arthur Armington died suddenly in 1937, leading to a stumble in Euclid's fortunes.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] George Armington died in 1954, at the age of 89, after overseeing the sale of Euclid to GM.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Sons Stuart & Everett Armington retired in 1953, and George Jr retired in 1958.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The youngest son Ray, the last Armington, retired in 1960 after seven years as General Manager of GM's Euclid Division.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The 1950s and 1960s were good years for Euclid Trucks.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] In 1951, the company produced the industry's first 50-ton, three-axle dump truck, with twin-engined Cummins power.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] During that period, Euclid produced two- and three-axle dump trucks with capacities up to 105 tons.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Some of the largest three-axle units were used as tractors for even larger end-dump, and bottom-dump haulers.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] In 1959, the Department of Justice, led by Attorney General William P.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Rogers, initiated an antitrust suit, under the Clayton Act, against General Motors Corporation.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] It charged that GM was too dominant, and its business methods stifled competition in the off-road hauler and earthmoving market.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] GM fought the suit for eight years, finally surrendering in 1968 and agreeing to sell its Euclid Division.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] After the sale of Euclid to White Motor Corporation, GM formed the Terex brand.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Under the sale agreement with White, GM was not allowed to produce trucks in competition with White for four years – from July 1, 1968, to July 1, 1972.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] GM could produce off-road haul trucks but could not sell them in the US.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] GM equipment dealers in the US were offered a franchise deal from White to sell the White/Euclid line of trucks for a period of four years.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The international Euclid dealerships were still owned by GM, thus forcing White to form all-new international dealerships.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] GM produced haul trucks in the 1968-1972 period that it had developed during its ownership of Euclid, using plants in Canada and Scotland that it had been allowed to keep.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] They were sold under the name Terex, but were essentially the same as the Euclid line.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The Euclid Company lost its prominence after the sale to White, and never achieved the standing that it enjoyed before the GM acquisition.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The following April, Clark formed a 50/50 joint venture with Volvo of Sweden, now known as Volvo Construction Equipment, to manufacture Volvo, Michigan and Euclid construction equipment under the name of VME Group NV.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] VME underwent several rather confusing reorganisation of its American and European operations, culminating in 1991 in the creation of a VME North Americas unit, to handle only the Euclid lines.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] In December 1993, VME North America entered into a joint venture of its own with Hitachi Construction Machinery Co.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Ltd., called Euclid-Hitachi Heavy Equipment.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Hitachi, a manufacturer of hydraulic construction machinery such as excavators and cranes, gradually increased its share of the joint venture until it owned 100% of the organization by 2000.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Hitachi obtained Euclid to fill the gap in their ability to offer a complete mining package, because mining excavators and dump trucks are usually needed in combination.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] During the transitional phase Hitachi utilized the Euclid brand name on some models and parts.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Production was moved from Euclid, Ohio, to Guelph in Ontario, Canada.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The trucks were are equipped with mufflers and computer controllers to meet environmental requirements for sound and exhaust emissions.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Smaller construction trucks using older technology, of 32 tons and 36 tons capacity previously manufactured in Poland under license from VME (Volvo Michigan Euclid) are being built in India by Telcon, a joint venture between Tata and Hitachi Construction Machinery Co.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid-Hitachi became Hitachi Construction Truck Manufacturing.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] On January 1, 2004, the Euclid name had been phased out ending 80 years of the Euclid name on construction machinery.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The Euclid company of Euclid, OH, was synonymous with off-road haul trucks, and earthmoving equipment such as bottom dumpers, and to a lesser extent, scrapers, in the 1950s.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Nichols' "Moving the Earth", now in its 5th edition, Euclid was everywhere.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] GM's work on heavy duty automatic transmissions during World War II had produced the Allison heavy duty automatic in 1945.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid was the first to use this transmission in heavy duty off-road dump trucks in the late 1940s.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] It met the need for an industrial transmission with huge power capacity, as engine sizes were increasing to the point where transmissions could not cope with the power.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid pioneered the use of twin engines (Twin-Power) in a bottom dumper (model 50FDT-102W), in November 1948.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Their first Twin-Power scraper prototype (model 51FDT-13SH) appeared in February 1949, and production model Twin-Power scrapers were released in 1950 (GM powered model 68FDT-17SH – and the Cummins powered model, 66FDT-16SH).
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Prior to GM's purchase of Euclid, the engine preferred by Euclid was Cummins diesels, with GM's 2-stroke Detroit Diesel offered as an option.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] When GM purchased Euclid, it led to dismay at Cummins, because of loss of an important customer.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The takeover led to GM engines being the engine of choice, but the Cummins option was still available, although Cummins-engined trucks sold in lower numbers after the GM takeover.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Ranging from 10 to 62 ton capacity, the giants roamed strip mines, heavy construction sites and quarries worldwide.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid's end dumpers reached 210 tons in capacity in the 1980s.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid trucks were usually loaded by cable-operated crawler shovels and draglines of other manufacturers, but Euclid also developed mobile belt loaders to load its bottom dump trucks.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid also pioneered the high speed tractor belly dumper.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] This combined an off-road tractor (with a fifth wheel) and a very large, up to 100-ton capacity, belly dump trailer.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] This machine, descended from bottom dump wagons drawn by crawler tractors, discharged its load through longitudinal gates in the bottom of the trailer.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] The first such trucks carried 13 cubic yards, but by the early 1960s capacities reached 110 tons.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid also manufactured wheeled tractor scrapers, such as were invented by R.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] LeTourneau (later to become LeTourneau-Westinghouse, after the purchase of R.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] G LeTourneau, Inc. by Westinghouse Air Brake Company) and now almost singularly manufactured by Caterpillar.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid's tractor scrapers were powered by the same tractors as their belly dumps.
[src:euclid-trucks/euclid-trucks] Euclid was the first major manufacturer to commercialize the articulated rubber tired loader, which is the current mainstay of many heavy equipment manufacturers, particularly Caterpillar.
